<div id="c24">
<p>Aaron,</p>

<p>That argument displays the exact circularity I&#8217;m talking about.  How do the &#8220;physics of consciousness&#8221; know that they have to &#8220;attach&#8221; to a brain that is conscious, but not a brain that is not conscious?  (Such as one of a person in deep sleep, a coma, recently deceased, or, say, the brain of a mosquito).  Do you have a way for the laws of physics to detect sufficiently complicated neural activity?</p>

<p>(This is notwithstanding that there is no reason for anyone to accept the existence of &#8220;qualia&#8221; in the first place, though I assume that is a premise of Searle&#8217;s argument.)</p>

<p>By the way, I didn&#8217;t accost Searle, I asked a question during the Q&amp;A session, and it was very much in the context of what he&#8217;d been talking about.</p>

